achsen, Tyskland","Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England":"Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Tyskland"},"nl":{"April 1409–1480":"april 1409–1480","1402–Male":"1402–Overleden","1405–Male":"1405–Overleden","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1405–1480":"1405–1480","1428–Male":"1428–Overleden","1435–1520":"1435–1520","1437–Male":"1437–Overleden","1385–Male":"1385–Overleden","1385–Female":"1385–Overleden","um 1428":"circa 1428","15 April 1409":"15 april 1409","1385":"1385","April 1409":"april 1409","1480":"1480","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1402":"1402","about 1437":"circa 1437","1520":"1520","1409":"1409","1428":"1428","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Sachsen, Duitsland","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Sachsen, Duitsland","Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England":"Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Duitsland"},"en":{"April 1409–1480":"April 1409–1480","1402–Male":"1402–Deceased","1405–Male":"1405–Deceased","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1405–1480":"1405–1480","1428–Male":"1428–Deceased","1435–1520":"1435–1520","1437–Male":"1437–Deceased","1385–Male":"1385–Deceased","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","um 1428":"about 1428","15 April 1409":"15 April 1409","1385":"1385","April 1409":"April 1409","1480":"1480","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1402":"1402","about 1437":"about 1437","1520":"1520","1409":"1409","1428":"1428","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Saxony, Germany","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Germany","Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England":"Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Saxony, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bauer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Erwin, Fritz, Helmut, Heinz, Manfred, Franz, Gerhard, Johannes, Wolfgang.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): status name for a peasant or nickname meaning ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’, from Middle High German <i>(ge)būr</i>, Middle Low German <i>būr</i>, denoting an occupant of a <i>būr</i>, a small dwelling or building. This word later fell together with Middle High German <i>būwære</i>, an agent noun from Old High German <i>būwan</i> ‘to cultivate’, later also (at first in Low German dialects) ‘to build’. The precise meaning of the Jewish surname, which is of later formation, is unclear. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Denmark, Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, Croatia, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic status names or surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Agricola","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Algert, Cornelis.  German Aloys, Otto.","German and Dutch: humanistic surname, a translation into Latin of German   Bauer   and Dutch   Boer   ‘farmer’."]},{"name":"Bauerlein","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Gunther.","German (<b>Bäuerlein</b>): standardized diminutive of   Bauer  , originally occurring in southern dialects as <b>Bäuerle</b> (see   Bauerle  ),   Beuerle  , and   Beyerle  ."]},{"name":"Baur","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Uli, Ulrich, Alfons, Arno, Erwin, Friedrich, Fritz, Urs, Wilhelm, Wolfgang.","South German: variant of   Bauer   ‘peasant’ or ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]},{"name":"Ankenbauer","meanings":["South German (mainly Bavaria): from Middle High German <i>anken</i> ‘butter’ + <i>būr</i> ‘farmer’ (see   Bauer  ), hence an occupational name for a dairy farmer. Alternatively, the first element may be a topographic term, <i>Anke</i>, meaning ‘slight rise in the ground’, or an old term <i>ank</i> ‘watery’, hence ‘farmer with fields in a wet area’."]},{"name":"Bierle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto.","South German: from a diminutive of   Bauer  , an unrounded form of Alemannic <b>Bürle</b> (compare   Buehrle  )."]},{"name":"Beurer","meanings":["(2010: NA)","South German: habitational name for someone from any of various places called Beuren, from Old High German <i>būr</i> ‘small dwelling’ (see   Bauer  )."]},{"name":"Bauerle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard, Albrecht, Helmut, Horst, Lothar, Merwin, Otto.","South German (<b>Bäuerle</b>): from a Swabian diminutive of   Bauer  ."]},{"name":"Bauers","meanings":["German: variant of   Bauer  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, or from a first part of an original compound name (e.g.   Bauersfeld  )."]},{"name":"Beuerle","meanings":["South German: diminutive of   Bauer  ."]},{"name":"Baumann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Otto, Gerhard, Ernst, Heinz, Guenter, Armin, Dieter, Erna, Friedrich.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): status name for a peasant or a nickname meaning ‘neighbor, fellow citizen’, from Middle High German <i>būman</i>, German <i>Baumann</i> ‘peasant’ (see   Bauer  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Denmark, Poland, and some other European countries. Compare   Bauman   and   Bowman  ."]}]},{"name":"Christian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Christianus</i> ‘follower of Christ’, in use as a given name from the Middle Ages onwards, especially as a girl's name. The name of <i>Christ</i> (Greek <i>Khristos</i>) is a translation of the Hebrew term <i>Messiah</i> ‘anointed’."],"variants":[{"name":"Christianne","meanings":["From Latin <i>Christianus</i> ‘follower of Christ’, in use as a given name from the Middle Ages onwards, especially as a girl's name. The name of <i>Christ</i> (Greek <i>Khristos</i>) is a translation of the Hebrew term <i>Messiah</i> ‘anointed’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Christian Bauer was born in April 1409, in Saxony, Germany, his father, Thomas Josef Bauer, was 25 and his mother, Bauer, was 24. He had at least 3 sons with Trautmann. He died in 1480, at the age of 71."},"et":{"April 1409–1480":"aprill 1409–1480","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1405–Male":"1405–Surnud","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1405–1480":"1405–1480","1428–Male":"1428–Surnud","1435–1520":"1435–1520","1437–Male":"1437–Surnud","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","um 1428":"umbes 1428","15 April 1409":"15. aprill 1409","1385":"1385","April 1409":"aprill 1409","1480":"1480","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1402":"1402","about 1437":"umbes 1437","1520":"1520","1409":"1409","1428":"1428","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Sachsen, Saksamaa","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa","Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England":"Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"April 1409–1480":"huhtikuu 1409–1480","1402–Male":"1402–Kuollut","1405–Male":"1405–Kuollut","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1409–1480":"1409–1480","1405–1480":"1405–1480","1428–Male":"1428–Kuollut","1435–1520":"1435–1520","1437–Male":"1437–Kuollut","1385–Male":"1385–Kuollut","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","um 1428":"noin 1428","15 April 1409":"15. huhtikuuta 1409","1385":"1385","April 1409":"huhtikuu 1409","1480":"1480","1437":"1437","1435":"1435","1402":"1402","about 1437":"noin 1437","1520":"1520","1409":"1409","1428":"1428","1405":"1405","Saxony, Germany":"Sachsen, Saksa","Schwarzenberg, Saxony, Prussia, Germany":"Kreis Schwarzenberg, Sachsen, Saksa","Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England":"Welwyn, Hertfordshire, England","Neundorf, Annaberg, Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany":"Neundorf, Kreis Annaberg, Sachsen, Saksa"},"fr":{"April 1409–1